WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.800
If I ask you to close your eyes, you know,

2
00:00:02.800 --> 00:00:04.720
and just picture a bright red apple,

3
00:00:04.720 --> 00:00:06.560
you can probably see it in your mind's eye.

4
00:00:06.560 --> 00:00:08.400
Right, the classic thought experiment.

5
00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:09.240
Yeah, exactly.

6
00:00:09.240 --> 00:00:11.000
You know, add to the curve of it,

7
00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:14.060
maybe even like a little reflection of light on the skin.

8
00:00:14.060 --> 00:00:15.200
But think about this for a second.

9
00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:16.640
Where is that picture?

10
00:00:16.640 --> 00:00:18.840
Well, it's definitely not inside your physical head.

11
00:00:18.840 --> 00:00:19.880
Exactly. Yeah.

12
00:00:19.880 --> 00:00:22.640
If a surgeon were to open your skull right now,

13
00:00:22.640 --> 00:00:23.880
they wouldn't find an apple.

14
00:00:23.880 --> 00:00:25.780
They wouldn't find a tiny movie screen

15
00:00:25.780 --> 00:00:27.560
playing back your memories.

16
00:00:27.620 --> 00:00:31.320
There's just, you know, wet biological tissue

17
00:00:31.320 --> 00:00:32.160
and electricity.

18
00:00:32.160 --> 00:00:33.620
Intermediate and chemical signals, yeah.

19
00:00:33.620 --> 00:00:34.460
Right.

20
00:00:34.460 --> 00:00:37.620
So how on earth does this lump of physical hardware

21
00:00:37.620 --> 00:00:41.320
create the incredibly rich, subjective experience

22
00:00:41.320 --> 00:00:42.160
of being you?

23
00:00:42.160 --> 00:00:43.560
It really is the ultimate puzzle.

24
00:00:43.560 --> 00:00:47.320
I mean, you can map every single neuron in the human brain,

25
00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:50.360
but pointing to a cluster of firing cells

26
00:00:50.360 --> 00:00:52.740
still doesn't explain the actual feeling

27
00:00:52.740 --> 00:00:54.720
of experiencing the color red,

28
00:00:54.720 --> 00:00:56.720
or, you know, the taste of coffee

29
00:00:56.840 --> 00:00:58.740
or that sudden feeling of nostalgia.

30
00:00:58.740 --> 00:01:01.540
Which is exactly what we are tackling today.

31
00:01:01.540 --> 00:01:04.400
Welcome to this deep dive into a really fascinating set

32
00:01:04.400 --> 00:01:06.540
of lecture notes and slides

33
00:01:06.540 --> 00:01:08.720
on the neuroscience of consciousness.

34
00:01:08.720 --> 00:01:10.280
Our mission today is to break down

35
00:01:10.280 --> 00:01:11.640
the core brain structures,

36
00:01:11.640 --> 00:01:13.080
the physiological functions,

37
00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:15.020
and the actual nuts and bolts of the mind.

38
00:01:15.020 --> 00:01:18.160
And we wanna do it without drowning you in academic jargon.

39
00:01:18.160 --> 00:01:20.520
We're focusing on the how and the why,

40
00:01:20.520 --> 00:01:22.760
so you can genuinely understand the machinery

41
00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:24.040
behind your own awareness.

42
00:01:24.040 --> 00:01:26.680
To anchor us before we get lost in that machinery,

43
00:01:26.760 --> 00:01:29.260
the slides offer a really strong

44
00:01:29.260 --> 00:01:31.680
foundational definition of consciousness.

45
00:01:31.680 --> 00:01:33.640
It defines it as our subjective awareness

46
00:01:33.640 --> 00:01:35.600
of ourselves and our environment.

47
00:01:35.600 --> 00:01:36.440
Right.

48
00:01:36.440 --> 00:01:39.260
It's the mechanism that allows us to assemble information

49
00:01:39.260 --> 00:01:41.760
from dozens of different sensory inputs,

50
00:01:41.760 --> 00:01:43.920
use that data to reflect on our past,

51
00:01:43.920 --> 00:01:46.040
adapt to whatever's happening right now,

52
00:01:46.040 --> 00:01:47.680
and then plan for the future.

53
00:01:47.680 --> 00:01:49.560
The sources use this driving analogy

54
00:01:49.560 --> 00:01:52.200
that I think bridges that definition perfectly

55
00:01:52.200 --> 00:01:53.540
to everyday life.

56
00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:54.840
Think back to the very first time

57
00:01:54.840 --> 00:01:56.320
you got behind the wheel of a car.

58
00:01:57.080 --> 00:01:58.760
Oh yeah, white knuckling the steering wheel.

59
00:01:58.760 --> 00:01:59.880
Exactly.

60
00:01:59.880 --> 00:02:02.560
Your conscious awareness had to hyper focus

61
00:02:02.560 --> 00:02:04.560
on every single detail,

62
00:02:04.560 --> 00:02:07.440
like how hard your foot was pressing the gas pedal,

63
00:02:07.440 --> 00:02:09.160
the exact angle of the mirrors,

64
00:02:09.160 --> 00:02:11.800
scanning the intersection, the sound of the engine.

65
00:02:11.800 --> 00:02:14.680
It consumes 100% of your mental bandwidth.

66
00:02:14.680 --> 00:02:16.240
It's exhausting because your brain

67
00:02:16.240 --> 00:02:20.480
is actively building new neural pathways in real time.

68
00:02:20.480 --> 00:02:23.520
But consider what happens after, say, 10 years of driving.

69
00:02:23.520 --> 00:02:24.920
You literally pull into your driveway

70
00:02:24.920 --> 00:02:27.680
and realize you don't even remember the last five miles.

71
00:02:27.680 --> 00:02:29.280
Yep, highway hypnosis.

72
00:02:29.280 --> 00:02:32.400
The complex act of driving has just become semi-automatic.

73
00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:34.240
Your conscious attention is suddenly freed up

74
00:02:34.240 --> 00:02:36.160
to focus on listening to a deep dive

75
00:02:36.160 --> 00:02:37.760
or planning what you're gonna make for dinner.

76
00:02:37.760 --> 00:02:40.280
And that transition from hyper focused effort

77
00:02:40.280 --> 00:02:43.520
to automatic processing highlights something crucial.

78
00:02:43.520 --> 00:02:45.920
Consciousness is a limited resource.

79
00:02:45.920 --> 00:02:48.200
But before we get into the biological mechanics

80
00:02:48.200 --> 00:02:50.160
of how the brain manages that resource,

81
00:02:50.160 --> 00:02:52.280
there is a short piece of media from the lecture

82
00:02:52.280 --> 00:02:54.840
to set a philosophical baseline for us.

83
00:02:54.840 --> 00:02:56.960
Pause for media, presenting idea

84
00:02:56.960 --> 00:03:00.480
that people are not their brains, 38 seconds long.

85
00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:02.720
Okay, so what that clip is getting at

86
00:03:02.720 --> 00:03:04.760
is a pushback against reductionism.

87
00:03:05.880 --> 00:03:07.320
It's challenging the assumption

88
00:03:07.320 --> 00:03:09.680
that a person is just their physical brain.

89
00:03:09.680 --> 00:03:11.080
Right, it introduces the idea

90
00:03:11.080 --> 00:03:13.840
that consciousness might be an emergent property,

91
00:03:13.840 --> 00:03:15.760
something that is more than just the sum

92
00:03:15.760 --> 00:03:17.360
of its biological parts.

93
00:03:17.360 --> 00:03:19.840
Which perfectly sets up the complex mechanics

94
00:03:19.840 --> 00:03:21.400
we are about to explore.

95
00:03:21.400 --> 00:03:24.240
Because if we are more than just the raw biology,

96
00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:26.200
we have to understand how that biology

97
00:03:26.200 --> 00:03:28.080
actually generates the mind.

98
00:03:28.080 --> 00:03:29.080
Section pause.

99
00:03:29.080 --> 00:03:32.440
So if that subjective experience is so mysterious,

100
00:03:32.440 --> 00:03:34.480
you might be wondering how neuroscientists

101
00:03:34.480 --> 00:03:37.040
actually measure or categorize it in a lab.

102
00:03:37.040 --> 00:03:38.520
We need some kind of map.

103
00:03:38.520 --> 00:03:41.240
And looking at the diagram on this slide in the notes,

104
00:03:41.240 --> 00:03:44.280
you can visualize this as a plot on a graph.

105
00:03:44.280 --> 00:03:46.800
On the vertical axis, we have level or state.

106
00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:48.680
Which is simply how globally awake

107
00:03:48.680 --> 00:03:50.800
or responsive you are to the outside world.

108
00:03:50.800 --> 00:03:53.120
It ranges from a deep comb at the very bottom,

109
00:03:53.120 --> 00:03:55.080
moves up through general anesthesia,

110
00:03:55.080 --> 00:03:56.560
then through the stages of sleep,

111
00:03:56.560 --> 00:03:59.280
all the way to full alert wakefulness at the top.

112
00:03:59.280 --> 00:04:02.520
Then, on a horizontal axis, you have content.

113
00:04:02.520 --> 00:04:04.680
This measures the vividness and complexity

114
00:04:04.680 --> 00:04:06.560
of what you are actually experiencing.

115
00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:09.240
Right, the sensory inputs, the emotions,

116
00:04:09.240 --> 00:04:11.240
thoughts and memories happening in your mind

117
00:04:11.240 --> 00:04:12.480
at any given moment.

118
00:04:12.480 --> 00:04:15.040
And plotting human experience on that graph

119
00:04:15.040 --> 00:04:17.920
reveals something the notes call dual processing

120
00:04:17.920 --> 00:04:19.400
or the two track mind.

121
00:04:19.400 --> 00:04:21.120
This is a huge concept.

122
00:04:21.120 --> 00:04:23.640
It turns out that our perception, our memory,

123
00:04:23.640 --> 00:04:25.280
our thinking, they all operate

124
00:04:25.280 --> 00:04:28.360
on two completely independent levels simultaneously.

125
00:04:28.360 --> 00:04:30.640
There is a high road and a low road.

126
00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:32.480
The conscious, deliberate high road

127
00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:34.200
is reflective and sequential.

128
00:04:34.200 --> 00:04:36.200
It processes things one at a time.

129
00:04:36.200 --> 00:04:38.760
But the unconscious, automatic low road

130
00:04:38.760 --> 00:04:40.480
is intuitive and parallel.

131
00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:42.600
It can process thousands of things at once.

132
00:04:42.600 --> 00:04:45.760
The slides show a visual model of this dual processing

133
00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:48.000
using the example of looking at a flying bird.

134
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:49.840
I think the easiest way to understand this

135
00:04:49.840 --> 00:04:51.640
is to imagine a theater.

136
00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:53.080
The unconscious low track

137
00:04:53.080 --> 00:04:55.920
is like a massive backstage theater crew.

138
00:04:55.920 --> 00:04:58.080
You have hundreds of crew members working in parallel,

139
00:04:58.080 --> 00:05:00.400
simultaneously calculating the bird's color,

140
00:05:00.400 --> 00:05:02.920
tracking its motion, defining its shape

141
00:05:02.920 --> 00:05:04.440
and judging its distance.

142
00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:06.400
And they're doing this automatically,

143
00:05:06.400 --> 00:05:09.120
incredibly fast and completely out of sight.

144
00:05:09.120 --> 00:05:11.880
Meanwhile, the conscious high track

145
00:05:11.880 --> 00:05:14.200
is the lead actor standing center stage

146
00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:15.880
under a spotlight.

147
00:05:15.880 --> 00:05:18.240
After the crew has done all the calculations,

148
00:05:18.240 --> 00:05:20.080
the actor sequentially and deliberately

149
00:05:20.080 --> 00:05:21.360
declares to the audience,

150
00:05:21.360 --> 00:05:23.560
I saw a red bird flying toward us.

151
00:05:23.560 --> 00:05:25.000
And the actor gets all the credit,

152
00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:27.120
but the crew did all the heavy lifting.

153
00:05:27.120 --> 00:05:29.720
Let's push that theater metaphor even further.

154
00:05:29.720 --> 00:05:33.040
If a heavy sandbag suddenly falls from the rafters,

155
00:05:33.040 --> 00:05:35.520
the backstage crew doesn't wait to tell the actor.

156
00:05:35.520 --> 00:05:37.160
They just pull the actor out of the way.

157
00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:38.480
Right, that's your flinch reflex.

158
00:05:38.480 --> 00:05:40.480
Exactly, by the time the lead actor looks up

159
00:05:40.480 --> 00:05:42.320
and says, whoa, that was close,

160
00:05:42.320 --> 00:05:43.800
the body has already moved.

161
00:05:43.800 --> 00:05:45.480
What's fascinating here is that we actually

162
00:05:45.480 --> 00:05:47.600
know more than we know we know.

163
00:05:47.640 --> 00:05:50.000
That backstage crew, the parallel processing,

164
00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:53.080
has to handle the vast majority of our routine

165
00:05:53.080 --> 00:05:54.840
survival-based business.

166
00:05:54.840 --> 00:05:56.680
Because sequential processing, the lead actor

167
00:05:56.680 --> 00:05:59.920
is computationally expensive and incredibly slow, right?

168
00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:00.760
Exactly.

169
00:06:00.760 --> 00:06:02.520
If you had to consciously calculate

170
00:06:02.520 --> 00:06:04.800
the trajectory of a falling object,

171
00:06:04.800 --> 00:06:07.720
you would be crushed before you finish the math.

172
00:06:07.720 --> 00:06:09.680
Consciousness is best saved for solving

173
00:06:09.680 --> 00:06:12.880
entirely new problems that require focused attention.

174
00:06:12.880 --> 00:06:14.200
Section pause.

175
00:06:14.200 --> 00:06:16.280
Let's talk about that focused attention.

176
00:06:16.280 --> 00:06:19.480
Because if the lead actor is so computationally expensive,

177
00:06:19.480 --> 00:06:21.080
we have to be really careful about

178
00:06:21.080 --> 00:06:22.680
where we point the spotlight.

179
00:06:22.680 --> 00:06:25.200
Yeah, the lecture notes describe selective attention

180
00:06:25.200 --> 00:06:27.920
using this flashlight analogy.

181
00:06:27.920 --> 00:06:30.680
Our awareness focuses like a flashlight beam

182
00:06:30.680 --> 00:06:34.520
on a tiny, minute aspect of all that we experience.

183
00:06:34.520 --> 00:06:37.680
It's an accurate metaphor because a flashlight

184
00:06:37.680 --> 00:06:41.880
only illuminates a tiny circle in a massive dark room.

185
00:06:41.880 --> 00:06:45.720
Whatever is inside the beam is your conscious reality.

186
00:06:45.720 --> 00:06:47.360
And everything outside that beam

187
00:06:47.360 --> 00:06:49.560
is actively suppressed by the brain.

188
00:06:49.560 --> 00:06:51.760
Wait, if it's a single flashlight beam,

189
00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:52.960
what happens when I'm, say,

190
00:06:52.960 --> 00:06:55.400
sitting in a boring meeting trying to listen to the speaker

191
00:06:55.400 --> 00:06:57.720
but I'm also under the desk texting a friend?

192
00:06:57.720 --> 00:07:00.200
I always feel like I'm multitasking pretty successfully.

193
00:07:00.200 --> 00:07:02.000
You're actually not multitesting at all.

194
00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:02.840
I'm not.

195
00:07:02.840 --> 00:07:05.200
No, the neuroscience is very clear on this.

196
00:07:05.200 --> 00:07:08.400
Human consciousness focuses on exactly one thing at a time.

197
00:07:08.400 --> 00:07:10.000
When you are typing that text message,

198
00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:12.800
the flashlight beam is entirely on your phone.

199
00:07:12.800 --> 00:07:14.200
In that specific millisecond,

200
00:07:14.200 --> 00:07:17.360
your brain is actively suppressing the speaker's voice

201
00:07:17.360 --> 00:07:19.400
as irrelevant background noise.

202
00:07:19.400 --> 00:07:21.520
So I'm just swinging the flashlight back and forth

203
00:07:21.520 --> 00:07:22.360
really fast.

204
00:07:22.360 --> 00:07:23.200
Precisely.

205
00:07:23.200 --> 00:07:25.360
You are rapidly task switching.

206
00:07:25.360 --> 00:07:27.120
And every time you swing that flashlight,

207
00:07:27.120 --> 00:07:28.680
there is a cognitive cost.

208
00:07:28.680 --> 00:07:30.640
You lose tiny pieces of information

209
00:07:30.640 --> 00:07:32.840
in the dark space between the two targets.

210
00:07:32.840 --> 00:07:34.200
Which is why task switching

211
00:07:34.200 --> 00:07:36.200
is highly inefficient and draining.

212
00:07:36.200 --> 00:07:37.040
Exactly.

213
00:07:37.040 --> 00:07:39.880
To really prove how narrow that flashlight beam is,

214
00:07:39.880 --> 00:07:43.920
the slides include a classic psychological experiment video.

215
00:07:43.920 --> 00:07:46.000
We're gonna pause so you can watch it.

216
00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:48.760
Be close attention to what the video ask you to count.

217
00:07:48.760 --> 00:07:50.320
Pause for media.

218
00:07:50.320 --> 00:07:53.100
Video challenging the selective attention of viewers.

219
00:07:53.100 --> 00:07:55.600
Stop or advance slides after three minutes.

220
00:07:55.600 --> 00:07:58.520
For anyone who hasn't seen that type of experiment before,

221
00:07:58.520 --> 00:08:00.320
it is always a visceral shock.

222
00:08:00.320 --> 00:08:01.480
Oh, absolutely.

223
00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:03.880
You are so focused on counting the passes

224
00:08:03.880 --> 00:08:06.840
that you completely miss the bizarre, obvious thing

225
00:08:06.840 --> 00:08:08.360
walking right through the middle of the screen.

226
00:08:08.360 --> 00:08:10.960
It perfectly demonstrates inattention blindness

227
00:08:10.960 --> 00:08:13.520
and its cousin, change blindness.

228
00:08:13.520 --> 00:08:15.040
At the level of conscious awareness,

229
00:08:15.040 --> 00:08:18.200
we are functionally blind to all but a tiny sliver

230
00:08:18.200 --> 00:08:19.880
of visual stimuli.

231
00:08:19.880 --> 00:08:21.680
We fail to see massive objects

232
00:08:21.680 --> 00:08:23.540
or huge changes in our environment

233
00:08:23.540 --> 00:08:25.800
simply because our attention is directed elsewhere.

234
00:08:25.800 --> 00:08:27.240
Because the flashlight was pointed

235
00:08:27.240 --> 00:08:29.120
at the assigned counting task,

236
00:08:29.120 --> 00:08:32.120
the backstage crew just decided the unexpected event

237
00:08:32.120 --> 00:08:35.400
wasn't important enough to bother the lead actor with.

238
00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:36.720
Section pause.

239
00:08:36.720 --> 00:08:39.120
We've talked about the psychology and the behavior,

