Exactly.

275
00:09:48.720 --> 00:09:51.120
Almost every piece of sensory information

276
00:09:51.120 --> 00:09:53.000
from your eyes, ears, and skin

277
00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:54.440
hits the thalamus first

278
00:09:54.440 --> 00:09:56.480
and it decides what gets forwarded up the chain.

279
00:09:56.480 --> 00:09:57.920
And what is at the top of the chain?

280
00:09:57.920 --> 00:10:00.060
The third pillar, the cortex.

281
00:10:00.060 --> 00:10:02.160
That wrinkled outer layer of the brain.

282
00:10:02.160 --> 00:10:05.600
The cortex is where the actual conscious contents,

283
00:10:05.600 --> 00:10:07.620
the vivid memories, the visual imagery,

284
00:10:07.620 --> 00:10:09.820
the complex thoughts are processed

285
00:10:09.820 --> 00:10:12.620
and integrated into that unified experience of you.

286
00:10:12.620 --> 00:10:15.700
Okay, so power supply, router, and processor.

287
00:10:15.700 --> 00:10:17.840
Now, how do doctors actually use

288
00:10:17.840 --> 00:10:20.460
this hardware map clinically?

289
00:10:20.460 --> 00:10:21.540
Because like we said at the beginning,

290
00:10:21.540 --> 00:10:23.180
you can't just x-ray a thought.

291
00:10:23.180 --> 00:10:25.420
This leads to one of the most profound applications

292
00:10:25.420 --> 00:10:26.260
in the notes.

293
00:10:26.260 --> 00:10:28.900
They describe an FMRI study involving a patient

294
00:10:28.900 --> 00:10:30.860
who had suffered severe brain trauma.

295
00:10:30.860 --> 00:10:34.720
Behaviorally, this patient was entirely non-communicative.

296
00:10:34.720 --> 00:10:37.140
She appeared to be in a vegetative state.

297
00:10:37.220 --> 00:10:39.580
Her eyes were open, but there was no response

298
00:10:39.580 --> 00:10:41.860
to voices, pain, or movement.

299
00:10:41.860 --> 00:10:43.520
So her state appeared to be awake,

300
00:10:43.520 --> 00:10:45.020
but her content appeared to be zero.

301
00:10:45.020 --> 00:10:46.300
Yes, exactly.

302
00:10:46.300 --> 00:10:49.460
But researchers put the patient in an FMRI scanner,

303
00:10:49.460 --> 00:10:51.460
which measures real-time blood flow

304
00:10:51.460 --> 00:10:53.780
to active areas of the brain.

305
00:10:53.780 --> 00:10:55.500
Through an intercom, they asked her

306
00:10:55.500 --> 00:10:57.180
to imagine playing a game of tennis.

307
00:10:57.180 --> 00:10:58.300
Wait, playing tennis?

308
00:10:58.300 --> 00:11:00.100
That requires complex motor planning.

309
00:11:00.100 --> 00:11:01.820
It does, and the blood rushed

310
00:11:01.820 --> 00:11:04.140
to the exact same supplementary motor areas

311
00:11:04.140 --> 00:11:05.980
as it would in a healthy volunteer.

312
00:11:06.020 --> 00:11:06.860
Oh, wow.

313
00:11:06.860 --> 00:11:09.420
So her brain was firing as if she was moving.

314
00:11:09.420 --> 00:11:10.380
Yes.

315
00:11:10.380 --> 00:11:12.180
Then they asked her to stop,

316
00:11:12.180 --> 00:11:15.600
and instead imagine walking from room to room in her house.

317
00:11:15.600 --> 00:11:17.680
This requires spatial mapping.

318
00:11:17.680 --> 00:11:19.300
Instantly, the activity shifted

319
00:11:19.300 --> 00:11:21.180
to the parahippocampal gyrus,

320
00:11:21.180 --> 00:11:23.380
which is the brain's spatial navigation center.

321
00:11:23.380 --> 00:11:25.020
That is wild.

322
00:11:25.020 --> 00:11:26.620
So the hardware was fully intact,

323
00:11:26.620 --> 00:11:28.380
and she was entirely conscious,

324
00:11:28.380 --> 00:11:30.340
listening and following instructions,

325
00:11:30.340 --> 00:11:32.380
even though her body couldn't move a millimeter.

326
00:11:32.380 --> 00:11:34.000
They basically used the brain scanner

327
00:11:34.160 --> 00:11:36.560
to establish a communication system.

328
00:11:36.560 --> 00:11:38.440
Imagine tennis for yes.

329
00:11:38.440 --> 00:11:40.440
Imagine your house for no.

330
00:11:40.440 --> 00:11:44.160
It proved undeniably that a lack of physical responsiveness

331
00:11:44.160 --> 00:11:47.080
does not equal a lack of conscious awareness.

332
00:11:47.080 --> 00:11:49.560
Moving from those hyper-focused clinical states

333
00:11:49.560 --> 00:11:51.000
to our daily lives,

334
00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:54.240
the slides introduce an incredibly interesting network

335
00:11:54.240 --> 00:11:57.960
called the Default Mode Network, or DMN.

336
00:11:57.960 --> 00:11:59.640
The DMN is fascinating.

337
00:11:59.640 --> 00:12:01.320
Yeah, the illustrations in the notes

338
00:12:01.320 --> 00:12:03.640
show a collection of specific brain regions

339
00:12:03.640 --> 00:12:05.560
right down the midline of the brain

340
00:12:05.560 --> 00:12:07.480
that suddenly synchronize and light up

341
00:12:07.480 --> 00:12:09.160
when an individual is not engaged

342
00:12:09.160 --> 00:12:11.800
in a specific externally focused task.

343
00:12:11.800 --> 00:12:12.640
Right.

344
00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:14.360
When your mental flashlight is turned on

345
00:12:14.360 --> 00:12:16.020
and focused on a math problem,

346
00:12:16.020 --> 00:12:17.880
the DMN powers down.

347
00:12:17.880 --> 00:12:19.620
But the second you put the flashlight down

348
00:12:19.620 --> 00:12:20.800
and just stare at the wall,

349
00:12:20.800 --> 00:12:22.400
the DMN turns on.

350
00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:25.300
It is active by default when you are at rest.

351
00:12:25.300 --> 00:12:26.160
Think about the last time

352
00:12:26.160 --> 00:12:27.520
you were taking a long shower

353
00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:29.120
or staring out the window of a train,

354
00:12:29.120 --> 00:12:30.480
and suddenly a brilliant idea

355
00:12:30.480 --> 00:12:32.480
or solution to a problem just popped into your head.

356
00:12:32.520 --> 00:12:33.840
That wasn't an accident.

357
00:12:33.840 --> 00:12:37.620
No, that was your default mode network taking over.

358
00:12:37.620 --> 00:12:39.280
When you let your mind wander,

359
00:12:39.280 --> 00:12:41.840
the DMN orchestrates self-reflection,

360
00:12:41.840 --> 00:12:44.720
it processes your social interactions from the day,

361
00:12:44.720 --> 00:12:47.640
and it connects disparate ideas to drive creativity.

362
00:12:47.640 --> 00:12:50.240
Which means the relentless modern pressure

363
00:12:50.240 --> 00:12:51.900
to always be looking at a screen,

364
00:12:51.900 --> 00:12:53.600
constantly digesting content,

365
00:12:53.600 --> 00:12:55.840
actively suppresses the DMN.

366
00:12:55.840 --> 00:12:58.600
Your brain physically needs you to daydream

367
00:12:58.600 --> 00:13:01.240
so it can strengthen those internal connections.

368
00:13:01.240 --> 00:13:02.280
Section pause.

369
00:13:02.280 --> 00:13:04.320
So the DMN is what happens when we rest,

370
00:13:04.320 --> 00:13:06.520
what happens when we go offline completely.

371
00:13:06.520 --> 00:13:09.400
Let's talk about altered states, specifically sleep.

372
00:13:09.400 --> 00:13:11.740
A lot of people think sleep is just a light switch.

373
00:13:11.740 --> 00:13:14.360
You are either conscious or unconscious.

374
00:13:14.360 --> 00:13:17.800
But the notes emphasize that sleep is a graded state.

375
00:13:17.800 --> 00:13:19.720
Our plot of state versus content

376
00:13:19.720 --> 00:13:21.160
applies perfectly here, right?

377
00:13:21.160 --> 00:13:22.120
It does.

378
00:13:22.120 --> 00:13:24.840
When you first fall asleep and enter non-REM sleep,

379
00:13:24.840 --> 00:13:27.080
your behavioral connection to the world drops,

380
00:13:27.080 --> 00:13:29.360
and internally, things are pretty quiet.

381
00:13:29.360 --> 00:13:30.720
Dreams are infrequent.

382
00:13:30.720 --> 00:13:32.920
But then, you cycle into REM sleep.

383
00:13:32.920 --> 00:13:33.880
Rapid eye movement.

384
00:13:33.880 --> 00:13:34.720
Yes.

385
00:13:34.720 --> 00:13:37.600
During REM, your brain essentially paralyzes your body.

386
00:13:37.600 --> 00:13:39.120
Muscle tone drops to near zero

387
00:13:39.120 --> 00:13:40.840
so you don't physically act out your dreams

388
00:13:40.840 --> 00:13:41.680
and hurt yourself.

389
00:13:41.680 --> 00:13:43.880
So your responsiveness to the outside world

390
00:13:43.880 --> 00:13:45.800
is extremely low.

391
00:13:45.800 --> 00:13:49.760
However, your internally generated conscious experience,

392
00:13:51.160 --> 00:13:53.320
the content is incredibly high.

393
00:13:53.320 --> 00:13:55.100
The topographic maps in the slides

394
00:13:55.100 --> 00:13:57.100
show us exactly what parts of the brain

395
00:13:57.100 --> 00:13:59.720
are lighting up and going dark during REM

396
00:13:59.720 --> 00:14:01.680
compared to when we are awake.

397
00:14:01.680 --> 00:14:03.140
And looking at this map explains

398
00:14:03.140 --> 00:14:05.320
why dreams are so deeply weird.

399
00:14:05.320 --> 00:14:07.440
The mechanics of dreaming are entirely based

400
00:14:07.440 --> 00:14:09.880
on which brain regions are granted power, right?

401
00:14:09.880 --> 00:14:10.880
Exactly.

402
00:14:10.880 --> 00:14:12.560
Why does a dream feel so bizarre,

403
00:14:12.560 --> 00:14:15.480
yet completely real and acceptable to you in the moment?

404
00:14:15.480 --> 00:14:17.840
It's because activity in your prefrontal cortex

405
00:14:17.840 --> 00:14:19.080
severely decreases.

406
00:14:19.080 --> 00:14:21.960
And the prefrontal cortex is the brain's logic center.

407
00:14:21.960 --> 00:14:24.160
It handles self-monitoring, critical thought,

408
00:14:24.160 --> 00:14:25.360
and reality checking.

409
00:14:25.360 --> 00:14:27.420
So the skeptical bouncer at the door of the club

410
00:14:27.420 --> 00:14:28.480
goes home for the night.

411
00:14:28.480 --> 00:14:30.440
And chaos ensues.

412
00:14:30.440 --> 00:14:32.000
With a reality checker offline,

413
00:14:32.000 --> 00:14:33.640
you don't question anything.

414
00:14:33.640 --> 00:14:35.360
You casually accept that you are suddenly

415
00:14:35.360 --> 00:14:36.620
grieving underwater,

416
00:14:36.620 --> 00:14:38.880
or that your living room just turned into a desert.

417
00:14:38.880 --> 00:14:40.640
Or that you were late for a college exam

418
00:14:40.640 --> 00:14:42.040
you already passed 10 years ago.

419
00:14:42.040 --> 00:14:43.880
Oh, I hate that one.

420
00:14:43.880 --> 00:14:46.200
And while the logic center is powered down,

421
00:14:46.200 --> 00:14:48.480
the emotion centers are throwing a party.

422
00:14:48.480 --> 00:14:51.360
Yes, the limbic and paralimbic structures,

423
00:14:51.360 --> 00:14:52.980
specifically the amygdala,

424
00:14:52.980 --> 00:14:55.060
which is your threat detection alarm,

425
00:14:55.060 --> 00:14:57.280
the anterior cingulate cortex,

426
00:14:57.280 --> 00:14:59.760
and the insula, they're all highly active.

427
00:14:59.760 --> 00:15:01.280
Because these emotional centers

428
00:15:01.280 --> 00:15:03.200
are firing on all cylinders,

429
00:15:03.200 --> 00:15:04.520
without any supervision

430
00:15:04.520 --> 00:15:06.980
from the logical prefrontal cortex,

431
00:15:06.980 --> 00:15:08.360
dreams are often characterized

432
00:15:08.360 --> 00:15:11.080
by extreme hyper-emotionality.

433
00:15:11.080 --> 00:15:14.100
You feel intense fear, joy, or anxiety.

434
00:15:14.100 --> 00:15:15.220
Wait, let me jump in here,

435
00:15:15.220 --> 00:15:17.320
because this raises a huge contradiction.

436
00:15:17.320 --> 00:15:18.620
If the prefrontal cortex,

437
00:15:18.620 --> 00:15:20.420
the logic and reality checking center

438
00:15:20.420 --> 00:15:22.400
is mostly offline during dreams,

439
00:15:22.400 --> 00:15:24.040
how do we explain lucid dreaming?

440
00:15:24.040 --> 00:15:26.300
I mean, I've had dreams where I suddenly realized,

441
00:15:26.300 --> 00:15:28.920
oh, I'm asleep, and I decided to start flying around.

442
00:15:28.920 --> 00:15:31.400
My logic center has to be awake for me

443
00:15:31.400 --> 00:15:32.880
to realize I'm in simulation, right?

444
00:15:32.880 --> 00:15:33.800
That is a brilliant catch.

445
00:15:33.800 --> 00:15:36.160
And the notes actually address this specific paradox.

446
00:15:36.160 --> 00:15:37.000
Yeah.

447
00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:38.760
Lucid dreaming is a highly unique,

448
00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:40.520
hybrid state of consciousness.

449
00:15:40.520 --> 00:15:41.960
What's happening in the brain then?

450
00:15:41.960 --> 00:15:44.540
Neural imaging shows that during a lucid dream,

451
00:15:44.540 --> 00:15:46.560
there is increased functional connectivity

452
00:15:46.560 --> 00:15:48.960
between the anterior prefrontal cortex,

453
00:15:48.960 --> 00:15:52.600
the APFC, and the temporal parietal association areas,

454
00:15:52.600 --> 00:15:54.600
which helps situate you in space.

455
00:15:54.620 --> 00:15:58.660
Wow, so a specific part of the reality checking network

456
00:15:58.660 --> 00:16:02.100
somehow manages to boot up and synchronize?

457
00:16:02.100 --> 00:16:04.460
Yes, it grants the dreamer

458
00:16:04.460 --> 00:16:06.940
waking level self-awareness and control

459
00:16:06.940 --> 00:16:07.860
while the rest of the brain

460
00:16:07.860 --> 00:16:10.600
remains fully immersed in the REM sleep state.

461
00:16:10.600 --> 00:16:12.300
It's basically hacking the hardware.

462
00:16:12.300 --> 00:16:13.140
Totally.

463
00:16:13.140 --> 00:16:15.580
And while we are on the topic of internal visualization,

464
00:16:15.580 --> 00:16:18.860
the slides briefly touch on a condition called aphantasia.

465
00:16:18.860 --> 00:16:20.560
This is a fascinating disorder

466
00:16:20.560 --> 00:16:23.520
where people completely lack the mind's eye.

467
00:16:23.540 --> 00:16:25.380
If I ask them to picture that red apple

468
00:16:25.380 --> 00:16:27.000
from the beginning of the deep dive,

469
00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:28.700
they see nothing but black.

470
00:16:28.700 --> 00:16:30.580
There is no visual imagery at all.

471
00:16:30.580 --> 00:16:32.900
And what's crucial to understand about aphantasia

472
00:16:32.900 --> 00:16:35.260
is how the lack of visual processing

473
00:16:35.260 --> 00:16:37.980
ripples out into other cognitive systems.

474
00:16:37.980 --> 00:16:40.740
It isn't just about not being able to imagine an apple.

475
00:16:40.740 --> 00:16:41.900
Right, the notes point out

476
00:16:41.900 --> 00:16:43.660
that many individuals with aphantasia

477
00:16:43.660 --> 00:16:45.780
report a significantly reduced ability

478
00:16:45.780 --> 00:16:48.380
to recall past autobiographical events,

479
00:16:48.380 --> 00:16:50.940
a reduced ability to imagine future scenarios,

480
00:16:50.940 --> 00:16:52.420
and fewer visual dreams.

481
00:16:52.440 --> 00:16:54.520
Because if you can't generate an image,

482
00:16:54.520 --> 00:16:56.800
you can't mentally time travel.

483
00:16:56.800 --> 00:16:59.200
It highlights how heavily our conscious architecture

484
00:16:59.200 --> 00:17:01.360
relies on visual simulation

485
00:17:01.360 --> 00:17:03.880
to construct our memories and our plans.

486
00:17:03.880 --> 00:17:05.440
Section pause.

487
00:17:05.440 --> 00:17:07.640
So is biological hardware

488
00:17:07.640 --> 00:17:10.260
with all its quirks and parallel processing

489
00:17:10.260 --> 00:17:12.840
can create this rich internal world

490
00:17:12.840 --> 00:17:15.520
what happens when we try to replicate it with silicon?

491
00:17:15.520 --> 00:17:17.240
Ah, yeah.

492
00:17:17.240 --> 00:17:19.320
We have to talk about artificial intelligence

493
00:17:19.320 --> 00:17:22.580
with current chatbots seeming so incredibly advanced.

494
00:17:22.580 --> 00:17:25.260
I mean, they can write poetry, debate philosophy,

495
00:17:25.260 --> 00:17:27.140
and pass the bar exam.

496
00:17:27.140 --> 00:17:28.100
Are they conscious?

497
00:17:28.100 --> 00:17:29.980
If we connect this to the bigger picture

498
00:17:29.980 --> 00:17:32.380
to answer that using the science from these slides,

499
00:17:32.380 --> 00:17:34.420
we have to draw a hard unforgiving line

500
00:17:34.420 --> 00:17:36.580
between performance and conscious experience.

501
00:17:36.580 --> 00:17:38.100
Okay, performance versus experience.

502
00:17:38.100 --> 00:17:40.320
Exactly, intelligence is not the same as consciousness.

503
00:17:40.320 --> 00:17:42.540
Performance asks, can the system use language,

504
00:17:42.540 --> 00:17:44.980
solve complex tasks, or predict outcomes?

505
00:17:44.980 --> 00:17:46.260
Conscious experience asks,

506
00:17:46.260 --> 00:17:48.860
is there something it is like to be the system?

507
00:17:48.880 --> 00:17:50.240
Does it feel anything?

508
00:17:50.240 --> 00:17:52.920
A good way to look at a current AI chatbot

509
00:17:52.920 --> 00:17:56.440
is to view it as a highly sophisticated digital parrot.

510
00:17:56.440 --> 00:17:59.480
It clearly has massive, large-scale

511
00:17:59.480 --> 00:18:01.480
language prediction capabilities,

512
00:18:01.480 --> 00:18:05.720
it recognizes patterns, and has extreme social fluency.

513
00:18:05.720 --> 00:18:08.880
But it completely lacks independent biological arousal.

514
00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:12.400
It has no homeostatic drives, it doesn't get hungry,

515
00:18:12.400 --> 00:18:15.080
it doesn't need to sleep to clear out metabolic waste,

516
00:18:15.080 --> 00:18:16.560
and it doesn't feel pain.

517
00:18:16.560 --> 00:18:17.920
And because of that,

518
00:18:17.920 --> 00:18:20.300
it has no grounded sensor motor experience

519
00:18:20.300 --> 00:18:21.420
in the physical world.

520
00:18:21.420 --> 00:18:24.220
The scientific stance outlined in the notes is firm.

521
00:18:24.220 --> 00:18:26.180
You cannot claim an AI as conscious

522
00:18:26.180 --> 00:18:28.100
based on its text behavior alone.

523
00:18:28.100 --> 00:18:30.240
Simulating talk about an experience

524
00:18:30.240 --> 00:18:32.660
is not the same as having the experience.

525
00:18:32.660 --> 00:18:35.140
The notes suggest a neuroscience-style approach

526
00:18:35.140 --> 00:18:36.620
to evaluating AI.

527
00:18:36.620 --> 00:18:38.980
Basically, a checklist of biological mechanisms

528
00:18:38.980 --> 00:18:40.100
that a system would need

529
00:18:40.100 --> 00:18:41.700
before we could even entertain the idea

530
00:18:41.700 --> 00:18:42.700
that it might be conscious.

531
00:18:42.700 --> 00:18:44.820
Right, there are three main criteria.

532
00:18:44.820 --> 00:18:46.600
First, recurrent processing.

533
00:18:46.620 --> 00:18:49.620
Current AI mostly relies on feed-forward data processing.

534
00:18:49.620 --> 00:18:51.300
Data goes in, an answer comes out.

535
00:18:51.300 --> 00:18:54.400
A conscious brain relies on massive feedback loops

536
00:18:54.400 --> 00:18:56.860
that constantly update its internal representations

537
00:18:56.860 --> 00:18:57.700
in real time.

538
00:18:57.700 --> 00:18:58.740
Okay, what's the second one?

539
00:18:58.740 --> 00:19:01.280
Second, it needs a global workspace.

540
00:19:01.280 --> 00:19:03.300
Like the thalmo-cortical loops we talked about.

541
00:19:03.300 --> 00:19:06.260
Exactly, a system that broadcasts information

542
00:19:06.260 --> 00:19:08.020
across its entire architecture

543
00:19:08.020 --> 00:19:10.980
for flexible, top-down control.

544
00:19:10.980 --> 00:19:13.300
Third, and perhaps most importantly,

545
00:19:13.300 --> 00:19:15.700
it needs embodied agency.

546
00:19:15.700 --> 00:19:18.040
Meaning, it needs a body.

547
00:19:18.040 --> 00:19:20.720
But why is that a requirement for consciousness?

548
00:19:20.720 --> 00:19:22.520
Because without a physical form

549
00:19:22.520 --> 00:19:24.080
interacting with an environment,

550
00:19:24.080 --> 00:19:27.000
taking actions that actively change its sensory inputs,

551
00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:28.760
a system has no stakes.

552
